// Starts the transaction, if not already started (used inside a method). If you call this multiple times after calling startTransaction() then it won't do anything. It will just make sure we are in one session where possible by using Hibernate internal state to keep track of sessions and use that instead when needed again
public Session currentSession();  // return the currently opened hibernate-managed database connection thread safe for other threads or non db operations, null if no transaction is active. Must not be called concurrently on a single session object (it must only call startTransaction() at most once). If this method returns true then it means that another request to open the same Session was launched before and hence should wait till all requests for opened sessions are completed
public boolean startTransaction(); // Begins transaction if not already started. Must be called on a single session object (it must only call currentSession() at most once). If this method returns true then it means that another request to begin the same Transaction was launched before and hence should wait till all requests for beginning transactions are completed
public void closeTransaction(); // closes transaction if started. Must be called on a single session object (it must only call startTransaction() at most once). It will stop tracking open sessions but it doesn't prevent other threads from manipulating the internal Hibernate Session state of this particular thread which means you can have two different calls to close-transaction while in middle if another operation is performed.
public void commit(); // If there are no pending changes, commits these transaction; otherwise throws an exception IllegalStateException because a caller must always either be calling startTransaction() or currentSession().setNewValue(...) on the same session before it calls this method (if you've started tracking open sessions with hibernate in your application).
public void rollback(); // If there are no pending changes, rolls back these transaction; otherwise throws an exception IllegalStateException because a caller must always either be calling startTransaction() or currentSession().setNewValue(...) on the same session before it calls this method (if you've started tracking open sessions with hibernate in your application).